s of opportunity, mostly linked to left-wing executive and legislative allies, can lead to improved rights even in a region as unequal as Latin America. Blofield also examines the conditions that lead to better enforcement of rights.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aEqualityxLatin America. 0aEqualityzLatin America. 0aHousehold employeesxSocial conditionsxLatin America. 0aHousehold employeeszLatin AmericaxSocial conditions. 0aIndustrial relationsxLatin America. 0aIndustrial relationszLatin America. 0aLabor movementxHistoryx21st centuryxLatin AmericaxLatin America. 0aLabor movementzLatin AmericaxHistoryy21st century. 0aSocial classesxLatin America. 0aSocial classeszLatin America. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271058894zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271058894423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271058894.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK